Problem 1. Dirichlet Distribution

A Dirichlet Distribution is a continuous distribution on \[A=\lbrace x = (x_1,x_2,...,x_d):x_i \geq 0 , \sum_{i=1}^{d}x_i = 1\rbrace \] with pdf \[ f(x) =\frac{\Gamma(\sum_{j=1}^{d}\alpha_j)}{\prod_{j=1}^{d}\Gamma(\alpha_j)}x_1^{\alpha_1-1}x_2^{\alpha_2-1}...x_d^{\alpha_d-1}\] We want to sample from this distribution.

1(a)Algorithm of Acceptance-Rejection Method

Step1: Set \(C = max_x \lbrace \frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \rbrace\)

Step2: Generate \(U_1Unif(0,1)\)

Step3: Generate \(X_2g(x)=g_X\)

Step4: Set \(X_1=X_2\) if \(U_1 \leq \frac{f(x_2)}{Cg(x_2)}\)

Note:

  1. Constraint : \(C \geq 1\)
  2. \(g(x)\) is the proposal.
  3. Domain of \(f\ g\) should be the same.

1(b)

Sample \(10^4\) data points.

\(d=3\) , \((\alpha_1,\alpha_2,\alpha_3) = (2,3,4)\) and \(g(x)\) is the uniform distribution on \([0,1]^3\)

Set \(g(x_1,x_2,x_3)Uni(0,1)^3\) with the pdf \(g(x_1,x_2,x_3)=1\)

fx <- function(x1,x2,x3){
  return((gamma(9)*x1*x2^2*x3^3)/(gamma(2)*gamma(3)*gamma(4)))
}
#proposal: uniform[0,1]^3
max_value <- 0
for (i in seq(0,1,by=0.001)){
  for(j in seq(0,1,by=0.001)){
    now <- fx(i,j,(1-i-j))
    if(now > max_value){
      max_value <- now
    }
  }
}
c<-floor(max_value)+1 
f_x1 <-rep(0,10000)
f_x2 <-rep(0,10000)
f_x3 <-rep(0,10000)
N <- rep(0,10000)
i = 1
repeat{
  x1<-runif(1,0,1)
  x2<-runif(1,0,1)
  x3<-(1-x1-x2)
  N[i]<-fx(x1,x2,x3)/c
  if(runif(1,0,1)<=fx(x1,x2,x3)/c){
    f_x1[i] = x1
    f_x2[i] = x2
    f_x3[i] = x3
    i = i+1
  }
  if(i == 10001){break}
}

1(c)Algorithm of Sampling Dirichlet distribution through Gamma distribution

Step1: Generate \(Y_i\Gamma(\alpha_i , 1)\) where \(i=1,2,...n\)

Step2: Set \(X_j = \frac{Y_j}{\sum_{k=1}^{n}Y_k}\) where \(j=1,2,...,n\)

Note

  1. \(\Gamma(\alpha_i , 1) = -\sum_{k=1}^{\alpha_i}\ln(U_k)\) where \(U_kUnif(0,1)\)

  2. \(X_j\) has a \(Dir(n,\alpha_1,...,\alpha_n)\) where \(j=1,2,...,n\)

Problem 2. Variance Reduction

We want to estimate the probability \[P \lbrace A=\sum_{i=1}^{N} > 10\rbrace \] \(X_i N(0,1) \ are \ i.i.d.\) and \(N Poisson(5)\) \(X_i \perp N\)

Sample \(10^5\) data points.

2(a)Naive Monte Carlo

Step1: Generate \(N Poisson(5)\)

Step2: Generate \(X_i Normal(0,N) \ i.i.d.\)

Step3: Set \(Y=1\) if \(\sum_{i=1}^{N}X>10\)

j<-1
Y <- rep(0,100000)
N <- rpois(100000,5)
repeat{
  if(sum(rnorm(N[j],0,1)) > 10){
      Y[j] <- 1
  }
  j=j+1
  if(j==100001){
    break
  }
}
Probability <- sum(Y)/length(N)
Variance <- 100000*Probability*(1-Probability)
## The Sample Mean by Naive Monte Carlo is :  0.00005
## The Sample Variance by Naive Monte Carlo is :  4.99975

2(b)Using B=N As Control Variate

Step1: Generate \(N Poisson(5)\)

Step2: Generate \(X_i Normal(0,1) \ i.i.d.\)

Step3: Set \(Y=1\) if \(\sum_{i=1}^{N} > 10\)

Step4: Set \(C = \frac{-cov(Y,N)}{var(N)}\)

Note

  1. The Control Variate : \(Var(Y+c(N-E[N]))\)
j<-1
Y <- rep(0,100000)
N <- rpois(100000,5)
repeat{
  if(sum(rnorm(N[j],0,1)) > 10){
    Y[j] <- 1
  }
  j=j+1
  if(j==100001){
    break
  }
}
c <- -cov(Y,N)/var(N)
C_V_reduction <- var(Y+c(N-mean(N)))
Mean <- mean(Y+c(N-mean(N)))
## The Sample Mean by Control Variate is :  0.00009
## The Sample Variance by Control Variate is :  4.985985

N <- rpois(100000,5)

2(d)Importance Sampling by N with Poisson(10)

Step1: Set the proposal \(g_N Poisson(10)\)

Step2: Generate \(N Poisson(10)\)

Step3: Set \(X = \frac{P(\sum_{i=1}^{n}X_i | N=n) \times f_N(n)}{g_N(n)}\)

Note

  1. \(f_N(n) Poisson(5)\)
f_N <- function(x){
  return(exp(-5)*5^x/factorial(x))
}
g_N <- function(x){
  return(exp(-10)*10^x/factorial(x))
}
N <- rpois(100000,10)
X<-rep(0,100000)
for(i in 1:length(N)){
  X[i] <- pnorm(10,0,sqrt(N[i]),lower.tail = FALSE)*f_N(N[i])/g_N(N[i])
}
## The Sample Mean by Importance Sampling by N is :  0.00007916308
## The Sample Variance by Importance Sampling by N is :  0.00000000150374

2(e)Importance Sampling by Xi with Normal(2,1)

Step1: Generate \(N Poisson(5)\)

Step2: Generate \(X_1,...,X_N Normal(2,1) \ i.i.d.\)

Step3: Set\(P(\sum_{i=1}^{N}X_i > 10)=\frac{1}{k}\sum_{j=1}^{k}I(\sum_{i=1}^{N}X_i > 10)\frac{f(X_1,X_2,...,X_N)}{g(Y_1,Y_2,...,Y_N)}\)

Note

  1. \(f(X_i) Normal(0,1)\)

  2. \(g(X_i) Normal(2,1)\)

f_g <- function(x){
  return(exp(-2*x+2))
}
X<-rep(0,100000)
N <- rpois(100000,5)
j<-1
repeat{
  Y <- rnorm(N[j],2,1)
  if(sum(Y)>10){
    X[j]<- prod(f_g(Y))
  }
  j<-j+1
  if(j==100001){
    break
  }
}
## The Sample Mean by Importance Sampling by Xi is :  0.00005885668
## The Sample Variance by Importance Sampling by Xi is :  0.000003958219

2(f)Importance Sampling by Xi with Normal(2,1) and N with Poisson(10)

Step1: Generate \(NPoisson(10)\)

Step2: Generate \(X_1,...,X_N Normal(2,1) \ i.i.d.\)

Step3: Set\(P(\sum_{i=1}^{N}X_i > 10)=\frac{1}{k}\sum_{j=1}^{k}I(\sum_{i=1}^{N}X_i > 10)\frac{f(X_1,X_2,...,X_N)}{g(Y_1,Y_2,...,Y_N)}\frac{h(n)}{l(n)}\)

Note

  1. \(f(X_i) Normal(0,1)\)

  2. \(g(X_i) Normal(2,1)\)

  3. \(h(n) Poisson(5)\)

  4. \(l(n) Poisson(10)\)

h_l <- function(n){
  return(exp(5)/2^n)
}
f_g <- function(x){
  return(exp(-2*x+2))
}
X<-rep(0,100000)
N <- rpois(100000,10)
j<-1
repeat{
  Y <- rnorm(N[j],2,1)
  if(sum(Y)>10){
    X[j]<- prod(f_g(Y))*h_l(N[j])
  }
  j<-j+1
  if(j==100001){
    break
  }
}
## The Sample Mean by Importance Sampling by Xi and N is :  0.00007166897
## The Sample Variance by Importance Sampling by Xi and N is :  0.00000339125

2(g)Prefered Sampling Method

In these sampling methods, importance sampling is better than any others, especially the method used in (f).

The target \(P \lbrace A=\sum_{i=1}^{N} > 10\rbrace\) is actuaaly a rare event. Thus, we need to sample a huge number of data points. However, by importance sampling, we can make the rare event become less rare, i.e.we do not need to sample such a huge number of sample points to do the estimation. Further, the bonus of importance sampling method is the variance reduction.

Problem 3. Bootstrap and Jacknife

Use the 20 data points with \(\hat{med}=0.3861\) to construct the confidence interval.

## The Sample Points :  0.0839 0.0205 0.3045 0.7816 0.0003 0.0095 0.4612 0.9996 0.9786 0.758 0.0002 0.731 0.0777 0.4483 0.4449 0.7943 0.1447 0.0431 0.8621 0.3273

3(a)Jacknife

Procedure

\[x_1,x_2,...x_{20}\] are the given 20 data points.

Set \[\hat{\theta_1}=\frac{x_2+...+x_{20}}{n-1}\] \[\hat{\theta_2}=\frac{x_1+x_3+...+x_{20}}{n-1}\] \[...\] \[\hat{\theta_{20}}=\frac{x_1+...+x_{19}}{n-1}\] \[n=20\]

Thus, \[\hat{\theta_o} = \frac {\hat{\theta_1}+...+\hat{\theta_{20}}}{n}= \bar{x}\] \[se^2 = \frac{n-1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n}(\hat{\theta_i}-\hat{\theta_o})^2\]

Theta<-c()
for(i in 1:length(Sample)){
  theta <- sum(Sample[-i])/((length(Sample))-1)
  Theta<-c(Theta,theta)
}
se_square <- ((length(Theta)-1)^2/length(Theta))*var(Theta)
bias <- (length(Sample)-1)*(mean(Theta)-mean(Sample))
MSE <- se_square + bias
lower_bound <- median(Sample)-1.96*sqrt(se_square)
upper_bound <- median(Sample)+1.96*sqrt(se_square)
## [Jacksknife] 95%-confidence interval: [ 0.2278262 , 0.5443738 ]

3(b)Bootstrap

In the given 20 data points, we resampling 20 points with replacement B times and get the \(\hat{\theta^*_i}\ i=1,2,...,B\) .The \(\hat{\theta^*_i}\) is the each mean of the resampling.

B = 10000
bootstrap_data = numeric(B)
for(i in c(1:B)){
  bootstrap_data[i] = mean(sample(Sample,length(Sample),replace = TRUE))
}
se_B_square = var(bootstrap_data) 
lower_bound <- median(Sample)-1.96*sqrt(se_B_square)
upper_bound <- median(Sample)+1.96*sqrt(se_B_square)
## [Bootstrap] 95%-confidence interval: [ 0.2300078 , 0.5421922 ]

3(c)Parametric Bootstrap

In Beta Distribution, we know that \(XBeta(\alpha,\beta)\) has the expectation and variance with \[E[X]=\frac{\alpha}{\alpha+\beta}\] \[ Var[X]= \frac{\alpha \beta}{(\alpha + \beta)^2(\alpha + \beta +1)}\] Thus, we could estimate the raw value of \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\)

## The Raw Value of Alpha is:  0.3555149
## The Raw Value of Beta is:  0.50412

Sampling \(10^4\)times from the raw estimate Beta Distribution as mentioned above.

Thus, we can get the new\(10^4\) \(\alpha\) and \(\beta\).

j<-1
N <- 10000
alpha <- rep(0,N)
beta <- rep(0,N)
repeat{
  K <- rbeta(10000,a,b)
  MM <- mean(K)
  VV <- var(K)
  al <- MM^2*(1-MM)/VV - MM
  be <- (1-MM)*al/MM
  alpha[j]<-al
  beta[j]<-be
  j <- j+1
  if(j==10001){
    break
  }
}
MSE_Alpha_hat <- sum((alpha-a)^2)/N
MSE_Beta_hat <- sum((beta-b)^2)/N
lower_bound <- median(Sample)-1.96*sqrt(MSE_Alpha_hat)
upper_bound <- median(Sample)+1.96*sqrt(MSE_Beta_hat)

## [Parametric Bootstrap] 95%-confidence interval: [ 0.3747172 , 0.4024735 ]
